column1: 256012;instagram;2018-11-06 23:14:36;FALSE;"6 de noviembre día nacional de la erradicación del feminicidio y desaparicion de mujeres

el 6 y 7 de noviembre de 2001 se encontraron en un campo algodonero de cd. juárez ocho cuerpos de mujeres tiradas y abandonadas a la intemperie. la denuncia de su desaparición se había realizado en meses anteriores por sus familiares.
hoy recordamos que a las madres y familiares de mujeres desaparecidas y asesinadas todavía no se les ha hecho justicia. con ello
column2: el propio estado se sostiene cómplice el feminicidio. • para no olvidar a todas las miles de mujeres asesinadas por violencia de género en este país.

column1: • para recordar que no son causas naturales sino acciones solapadas con impunidad y simulación las que sostienen y perpetúan el feminicidio.
• para denunciar que la violencia feminicida es una realidad en cada rincón de nuestro país.
• para exigir que el estado a través de cada una de sus instituciones cumpla con la sentencia de campo algodonero
column2: dictada por la corte interamericana de derechos humanos.

column2: ” she mentioned how comfortable she was about her actions. ""i think (""playboy"") was very empowering and no one forced me to do anything
column3: she said. ""i think this feminism can go too far – i'm a feminist but i think that this third wave feminism is a bore
column4: i think it paralyzes men i think that this me too movement is a bit too much for me. i'm sorry; i'll probably get killed for saying that.""

column5: i think that some things are just common sense. or if you go

column1: from 1870 to 1955 schools like dunbar high school in washington dc equaled or scored higher on standardized test scores than white schools.
from 1890 to 1950 every census report showed blacks at a higher participation rate in employment than whites.
in 1950 72% of black men had been married.
in 1950 81% of black women had been married.
black poverty was on the decline.
less black families were on government assistance.
black income was on the rise for black population in comparison to whites.
in 1965 76.4% of black children were born to married women.

the french connection was a scheme through which heroin was smuggled from turkey to france and then to the united states through canada. the operation reached its peak in the late 60s and early 70s
column2: and was responsible for providing the vast majority of the heroin used in the u.s

column1: 256115;instagram;2018-11-07 00:59:33;FALSE;"today started off to be some kind of day... when i was 20yo i went on a date to the movies with someone i had hung out with and kissed on and off through my teenage years...when he drove me home (i was living with my sister
column2: at this point my mom was already living in fl) he asked to use the bathroom. i was reluctant as my sister was away and said “no boys” against my judgment i brought him upstairs. what happened next i just remember screaming no
column4: then lots of blood. i was date raped. the neighbors heard me screaming
column7: and told my sister i had a boy over. i was asked to leave since i disobeyed the rules. i never reported it. why you ask. when i was 11 i was molested by a man. i told adults and they didn’t believe me. i thought here i am a 20 yo woman
column8: i went out on a date with him willingly
column10: and had a history of dating him. he was also an extremely good looking guy. who will believe me ? i then found myself homeless at 21yo. i am grateful for that. i got a real job
column13: and i had the best of times.

column1: this morning that person followed me on ig and sent me a dm asking how i was as if nothing ever happened. i was a little shook at first
column2: then angry. i reached out to someone asking what should i do. he said do what’s right for you. i then went within. i decided to practice what i preach. what i discovered was this was yet another test
column3: another learning and healing curve. i needed to forgive him and to forgive myself. which i did. it wasn’t his fault
column5: it was our life journey and i am ok. i forgive him and i blocked him. for i now have boundaries and respect for myself. i now love myself. i am not that girl i once was who was someone’s victim. i am powerful

column1: when you first see this side by side
column2: what do you see?  you may see a shorter haircut

column1: you can see on the right a girl with more wrinkles
column2: aging eyes from years of a hard story
column3: lots of gray hair that’s covered by my amazing stylist @kbirdhair and a bit of a smirky confidence that says “no matter what stone you throw

column1: here’s what you don’t see.  the evening after the picture on the left was taken
column2: i was forced to perform pleasurable actions on someone in authority in my place of work.  i had posted the picture on facebook from work because the sun caught me in a way that made me feel pretty
column3: so i posted it on a break.  it popped up on my fb memories today and stopped me in my tracks. i remember that day
column5: and i remember being scared in a dark office after hours. .

column1: the girl on the left was wounded
column3: and entirely without confidence. i had no voice
column4: and had no idea how to use it.  today....i am standing proud in my voice. i use my voice to make sure i am seen as a person
column5: not property. i use my voice to help others find theirs
column6: and i hope to one day share it with the world 🌎 .

column1: 256255;instagram;2018-11-07 03:52:08;FALSE;"e v e n t // the colors of our scars #advocate #idaho ——————————————————————

column2: the colors of our scars dance show is in 2 days! the colors if our scars is a dance show first and foremost about domestic abuse. its main purpose is to raise awareness and help us all recognize unhealthy relationships in our lives. however
column3: the show goes deeper than that. it tells a story about finding joy in our darkest and hardest experiences by focusing on the brighter colors of our lives. we can all change the colors of our scars.

column2: ” she mentioned how comfortable she was about her actions. ""i think (""playboy"") was very empowering and no one forced me to do anything

column4: i think it paralyzes men i think that this me too movement is a bit too much for me. i'm sorry; i'll probably get killed for saying that.""

column1: in the 20 years that i’ve been eligible to vote
column2: i’ve only voted in presidential elections. i never felt compelled to vote in lower level races. i don’t think this experience is unique to me. i think it’s the norm for my generation. this year
column3: i’ve now voted in a primary and a midterm.

column1: if the trumpster has a positive legacy
column3: embarrassing and atrociously unconscionable behavior has galvanized many of us out of apathy and inspired us to take a greater interest in what’s happening around us.

column1: i also believe that it was his election—the election of a man who openly bragged about sexual assault and made no real apologies for it—that finally propelled the #metoo movement out of the shadows and into a place where people are finally talking about what behavior is and is not okay. this discussion is long overdue.
i voted today because i want my kids’ generation to grow up in a nation where the truth and facts matter... in a nation that practices empathy and kindness—for all
i want their generation to respect knowledge
column3: considering all perspectives. i pray they learn to put themselves in the shoes of those from other walks of life and make decisions based on what’s best for everyone—not just themselves.

column1: i don’t know how things are going to work out tonight. but i do know that i’m going to keep paying attention and continue speaking my mind. this is probably going to be a long fight. but i believe in the greater good of this nation and i believe that justice

column1: 256353;instagram;2018-11-07 05:45:53;FALSE;"i call those affected by sexual violence ""survivors."" i have spent the better part of a year waiting to feel some magical transition from ""victim"" to ""survivor
column2: as if one day i would conquer the key to stopping all of the immeasureable pain havoc wreaked on my life. truthfully
column3: i have yet to feel like a survivor. on most days
column4: i feel robbed and like i am grieving for a version of myself that i am not sure exists anymore. but more importantly
column5: every victim/survivor deserved the right to claim whatever term makes then feel the most comfortable or more accurately represents their feelings.

column2: we must use our language intentionally. something bad did not happen to me. someone did something bad to me. that someone raped me. it was not an accident

column1: feminina och maskulina. med #metoo satte en rörelse igång i vårt förhållningssätt. inte bara till hur män bemöter kvinnor utan också till hur förlegade maktstrukturer gör oss förvirrade och avskärmade från hjärtats väg - som istället för makt som förtrycker styrs av makten vi kan känna i gemenskap snarare än olika läger

column1: mina funderingar spinner vidare på #metoo och hur jag kan medverka i att kunna integrera det i min verksamhet som yogini.

jag har samtidigt en längtan att känna kärleken till mitt väsen och varande som kvinna. jag har mött upp denna längtan främst i kontakten med mig själv och i systerskap med andra kvinnor. på kurser och festivaler. i cirklar och på retreats. under senaste året har jag träffat magiska människor som jobbar på olika sätt med att skapa kontakt med det inre feminina. det som längtar efter att bli bemött i både sin kraft och sin sårbarhet.

@astridbrinck astrid brinck är en av de kvinnor och lärare som gjort störst avtryck på mig detta år av att möta min sanna feminina natur. hennes lärande handlar inte bara om att jag duger som jag är - jag är radikalt värdig all (själv)kärlek! som kvinna i mitt djup mellan yin och yang får jag ta beslut inifrån denna vetskap om radical worthiness - som är en av astrids huvudteman i hennes kurser.
astrid kommer till sverige i november för en kurs i inner leadership for women. hon är innan utbildningen här i stockholm på yogini nästa onsdagkväll den 15/11 - 3 timmar för kvinnor

column1: blurb: the end of an era?

2018 heralds more than a few changes in the landscape of world-politics. in particular american politics with the ongoing mid-terms being called as i am writing this. and it is in these times of change that we also bid farewell to one of the most significant and relevant political-dramas of recent memory (and perhaps of all time)
the final season of the shakespearean extravaganza that was house of cards delivered what was promised but with a few caveats. unlike previous seasons
column2: this one is perhaps the most allegorical
column3: which is understandable given the rather tangible absence of a certain southern gentleman. however
column4: the show has always managed to be prophetic in its depictions of power-hungry politicians and their machinations and this season was no different.

column1: in the wake of metoo movement
column2: and the subsequent dismissal of kevin spacey
column3: the final season of the show has not only done away with its male lead
column4: but it also wants to do away with the notion of ""it's a mans world"". robin wright as claire hale is not just playing the part of the first woman to hold the most powerful political seat in the world
column5: but she is akin to pope pius ix as she goes about castrating the statues of male-egos which have been erected in and around the white house. for those who say ""there's no house of cards without kevin spacey"" this season goes beyond the realm of television to address the basic premise that it's a ""mans job"" to keep the world spinning.

column1: the only downside to the season is that the final episode leaves things a bit too open-ended. this however
column2: depends on how you wish to view things. is it the beginning of the end? or the end of an old beginning?

column5: every victim/survivor deserved the right to claim whatever term makes then feel the most comfortable or more accurately represents their feelings.

column2: we must use our language intentionally. something bad did not happen to me. someone did something bad to me. that someone raped me. it was not an accident

column2: or will do so with victim blaming and stigma. .

there has much #deep work that has been done (and continues) to move into and through my self. through years
column6: beyond. personally being told at a very young age and into adulthood i was not enough
column7: nor would ever be enough. and other lies. hurtful responses & #actions from others
column8: because of their hurt. that any time i would step up for/to my family
column10: or challenge what i knew was not healthy nor positive treatment
column11: i would receive such negative forms of reactions.

column1: it took me a long time
column4: to accept...that is not me. rather others coming from their own #pain. their own darkness. their own work that has not been faced.

column1: growing up in the professional soccer world. playing. coaching. male dominant field. ego fueled. based upon competition and winning
column2: though preaching development. what can i do
column4: i now see my true friends. fortunate to have a club coach as mentor. father figure. he helped save my life and is still a huge part of it. but that is rare. and unfortunate. i change that cycle for those i coach. mentor.

column1: i continue to work on the power of finding my #voice. clearly. confidently. compassionately. while #honest and standing up for the all of me that i am
column2: that i continue to #evolve towards. and now that i am stepping more and more into my #light
column3: this voice...i will #share and #sing this process of #empowerment with others. to #embody #courage and #live my most #authentic #self!!! 💫💕🙇🏽‍♀️ grateful for your taking the time and space to listen. read. i see you. me too. my mirror. 🙏🏽🙇🏽‍♀️🕉

column1: 256684;instagram;2018-11-07 15:13:29;FALSE;"purchase our hoodies coming soon so more people like sonia can feel happy and whole again.

column2: her high school boyfriend raped her at a hotel. she blocked the memory out of her mind to avoid dealing with it. then
column4: sonia was raped again. a man that she’d gone on a date with drove her to a junkyard late at night.

column2: sonia reported the incident to the police. the detective suggested she go to the hospital to be examined. one of the nurses in the er told her about the boston area rape crisis center (barcc).

column1: sonia called barcc’s hotline. “i needed to get help or i would have committed suicide

she received individual counseling at barcc.in her words: “sharon [sonia’s counselor] helped me process so many issues. she really made a difference in my life. i have a hard time imagining my healing without her.” sonia was also part of a 12-week group counseling program with other survivors. in these groups
column2: survivors work through the many common struggles they face. the sessions helped sonia realize she was not alone. “today
column3: i am feeling a lot stronger. i am happy and whole.” .

column1: this testimony was taken from the barcc website. checkout their website for more inspiring testimonies.

這幾天看了好幾則 #metoo ，可以發現很多兒少性侵或是性侵未遂的加害者往往都是身邊的親人。
你會說，孩子還小，為什麼要學這些，但這些施暴者從來不覺得這些孩子太小。
上大學英文課的作業是寫關於stand up comedy的論文，但老師給的gender stereotype範本充滿了滿滿的父權，我們不是要批判，而是被要求點出裡面有哪些觀點並贊成。
這樣助長性別刻板印象的行為，真的讓我感到噁心，老師可能不知道這樣的言論，這樣讓人哈哈大笑的show，對於性少數而言多麼殘忍。
性平教育是一把最有力的保護傘，唯有正視性暴力、身體分際，擁有正確的性觀念才能保護自己，還有學習不去傷害他人。

column1: 256698;instagram;2018-11-07 15:23:06;FALSE;"exciting to see this pass in my new state of utah!

it seems that eventually this will be legalized and prescribed everywhere and i am hopeful that many people will discover the healing benefits and we can reduce the alcohol and opioid consumption in our country.  so many people are quick to say there is potential for abuse but there are already many more harmful drugs readily available and everyone should have access to medical cannabis for pain relief.

i am thankful that when my brother's finger was bitten off we were in california where he had access to non opiod pain relief and know that had i not been there to fight for him he would have taken the drugs prescribed by the doctor.  instead i informed them he was a recovering alcoholic with 87 days sober and we were not interested in anything addictive.  we compromised on a small amount of prescription pain killers but he only used them briefly and did not become addicted and used cannabis thereafter.

it's time to stop our uneducated and uninformed bias around a plant that can help people not get addicted to pain killers and alcohol.  i am happy to be moving forward to a state that is actually more progressive than where i currently live which is literally stuck in the dark ages

i am thankful that when my brother's finger was bitten off we were in california where he had access to non opiod pain relief and know that had i not been there to fight for him he would have taken the drugs prescribed by the doctor.  instead i informed them he was a recovering alcoholic with 87 days sober and we were not interested in anything addictive.  we compromised on a small amount of prescription pain killers but he only used them briefly and did not become addicted and used cannabis thereafter.

column1: as i’m chugging my liquid energy in preparation for the work out i’m about to do — i was flipping through some photos from our honeymoon. .
i remember taking this and saying “woah! that’s a long way down!” .
we climbed so many stairs — so many hills and reached the top of cliffs and mountains throughout our trip. it was exhaustingly fun! .
looking at this photo today — i thought of this as metaphor for my life and how far i’ve come. .

🔥i’ve become an actual functioning adult. 🔥i’ve overcome so many of my fears. 🔥i become stronger every day. 🔥i’ve stayed true to myself. 🔥i’ve grown to be 100% unapologetically myself. 🔥i’ve battled mental instability. 🔥i’ve overcome self-mutilation. 🔥i’ve survived mental
column3: and sexual abuse. 🔥i’ve experienced great loss. 🔥i’ve decided to not let my chronic illness control me. .

column1: all in all — i’ve decided to work on becoming the person i was meant to be — not who others think i should be. .
as i remember standing on top of the cliffs of moher i want to keep this feeling forever. .
🌟the climb of life is often a difficult and daunting task. we all experience peaks and valleys
column2: but what’s important is how we interpret them and decide to do with the lessons they bring. when you’re feeling low
column3: remember: there’s always another peak on the other side of your valley. ♥️ .

column1: and the sight from your peak? it’s breathtaking..
as i’m chugging my liquid energy in preparation for the work out i’m about to do — i was flipping through some photos from our honeymoon. .
i remember taking this and saying “woah! that’s a long way down!” .
we climbed so many stairs — so many hills and reached the top of cliffs and mountains throughout our trip. it was exhaustingly fun! .
looking at this photo today — i thought of this as metaphor for my life and how far i’ve come. .

🔥i’ve become an actual functioning adult. 🔥i’ve overcome so many of my fears. 🔥i become stronger every day. 🔥i’ve stayed true to myself. 🔥i’ve grown to be 100% unapologetically myself. 🔥i’ve battled mental instability. 🔥i’ve overcome self-mutilation. 🔥i’ve survived mental

column1: 256788;instagram;2018-11-07 16:57:02;FALSE;"يعتقد أغلب الذين يظنون أنهم يمارسون الغزل وينتهي بهم المطاف كمتحرشين أن الضحية كان يجب عليها أن تتصرف بطريقة معينة حيال كلماتهم. يفترضون سيناريو خاصًا بهم، لربما هو الأبعد عن الواقع، وما أن تُبدي الضحية عدم تجاوبها وتبدأ أحلامهم بالانهيار، فإنهم يُصابون بالإحباط والغضب في الوقت ذاته. أحيانًا، ما يبدو ناعمًا وبسيطًا يحمل أسفل منه عدوانية وشهوانية تسعى بكل ثقلها لغزو الآخر. هكذا هو الأمر بعين الضحايا.⠀

تقول دراسة إن التحرش الجنسي مرتبط بشكل كلي بحجم السلطة الممنوحة، في حالة زيادة حجم السلطة لهذا الشخص فإن احتمالية استغلاله الجنسي للآخرين تزيد، خصوصًا لو كان ذكرًا، ولكنه أمر ينطبق كذلك على النساء ممن تملكن السلطة بصورة مفاجئة.⠀

column1: 256803;instagram;2018-11-07 17:04:16;FALSE;this is it for awhile - even i couldn’t wait for the mailers to stop coming and the commercials to go back to that for junk food.  but my thoughts this morning as i let it all sink in over morning coffee - the women’s marches mattered! - thank you to the women i know who have participated.  the #metoo movement has mattered - thank you to those who shared their stories to shed light on your own experiences.  women won in record numbers! the march for science mattered - 6 scientists were elected last night and we now have someone who believes in climate change in charge of the space
column2: science and technology committee.  #marchforourlives matters - we voted out a record breaking number of nra backed candidates.  #blacklivesmatter matters. supporting the lgbtq community matters.  and our youth matters - they got out in record numbers and made a difference!  so inspired by voter turnout.  so grateful for the leaders of all the above organizations.  so proud of my kids.  feeling hopeful and reinvigorated. 🇺🇸🇺🇸🇺🇸;;en;#metoo

column1: 256866;instagram;2018-11-07 18:13:00;FALSE;"the boys in my elementary school and high school severely harassed me
column2: especially when it came to sports. i was always tall
column4: and had a loud voice. that didn’t sit well with many of my peers. all legs and all heart
column5: i was a fearsome opponent on the track and on the dodgeball courts. when i’d run fast or win a game
column6: it made me an even bigger target 🎯. “yo giraffe
column7: how many pull ups can you do?” “i didn’t know trees could run.” “you look funny when you run

column1: so i stopped running for a while. the culture at my school growing up wasn’t what i want for my nieces or any young women finding themselves.  women are strong
column4: and we deserve a fist bump and a good game too after we mercilessly slaughter you at the cross country meet and dodgeball games 😇⚡️⚡️⚡️⚡️. if i had @girlsontheruninternational at my schools
column6: maybe i’d have taken running more seriously in my younger years and i’d be training at the nike track in portland right now. you can do something about this. support women
column7: support young girls who benefit from these volunteer programs to teach our female youth the skills and provide them the motivation they need to thrive in a “boys will be boys” world. .

column1: 256869;instagram;2018-11-07 18:30:01;FALSE;"🌸🌼🌸""desde hace años he tenido una gran pelea con comprender quién soy realmente... he sido constante en querer mejorar y fácilmente lo logro al creer en mí
column2: pero han sido recaídas de gran tamaño las que me empujan a perder lo que empiezo. por mi parte soy de no tener mucha estabilidad emocional pero realmente me considero una mujer fuerte con un gran corazón... una variedad de situaciones han sido grandes retos
column4: pues hace 3 años cumplí una de mis mayores metas y sueños
column5: del cual me siento al extremo orgullosa. opino que es un gran reto día a día ser mujer
column6: especialmente una con ganas de crecer y expanderse. pero así como es un gran reto sus resultados son increíbles
column7: no existe algo más importante que confiar en ti misma
column8: la mujer es un ser extraordinario y en cada una de ellas existe un cohete dispuesto a explotar y volar
column9: la clave siempre será estar feliz con lo que haces
column10: tener convicción en ti y jamás caer en un conformismo. el humano es un ser destinado a sólo pequeños aterrizajes de sus pies en tierra
column11: es mejor una mente por los aires motivándose a vola

column2: nel corso della nuova puntata di “#cr4 – la repubblica delle donne”
column3: in onda questa sera alle 21.25 su retequattro
column4: ha intervistato asia argento sullo scoop del settimanale chi che l’ha immortalata in compagnia di fabrizio corona
column5: annunciando di fatto loro relazione. l’attrice si racconta e spiega il suo punto di vista anche sullo scandalo weinstein
column6: sul movimento #metoo e sul caso jimmy bennett. di seguito alcuni stralci.

column1: sul freschissimo rapporto sentimentale con fabrizio corona
column2: la argento commenta: «prima di tutto vorrei dire che fabrizio l’ho visto due volte
column3: lasciatecela vivere e stiamo calmi! la nostra non è un’attrazione che deriva dal “fascino del male”
column4: quanto dal caos. fabrizio? mi sono fatta l’idea di un uomo profondo
column7: con delle idee profonde e interessanti. un po’ matto e caotico come me… e poi
column8: è troppo bello!». e aggiunge: «ancora non mi fido di lui
column9: ma non bisogna necessariamente fidarsi per provare passione o fremiti nel cuore. anzi
column10: a volte il non fidarsi è ancora meglio! io non voglio cambiare nessuno e spero che nessuno provi a cambiare me: se cambierò
column11: è solo perché lo deciderò io». quando le viene chiesto come fabrizio l’abbia conquistata
column12: dice: «fabrizio credo che si adatti un po’ in base ad ogni donna: con me lo fa parlandomi
column13: raccontandomi la sua storia e condividendo le esperienze. io ero molto legata a suo padre
column15: quindi avevo un occhio di riguardo per lui e conoscevo le sue origini nobili. con il padre avevo un bellissimo rapporto
column16: eravamo veramente amici: non mi aveva mai presentato fabrizio
column17: ma un altro figlio. quando vedo fabrizio
column18: sento che suo padre aleggia intorno a lui». sul fatto se attualmente si reputi felice
column19: l’attrice dice: «dipende dai momenti della giornata: a volte sono serena
column21: ma forse adesso sto un pochino meglio».

column2: but considering the amount of  uncomfortable comments i get when i go for a run or work out

column1: i was walking home after a run
column2: and some older dude with alcohol breath (mind you it was around 10am..) commented on my legs...when i told him i found his comment creepy
column3: he actually started yelling at me.... because you know he is a former ski coach and know what he is talking about...let's hope he never coached a women's team!!

column1: there also is a slightly uncomfortable situation at the gym i go to that i yet have to address properly. an older
column2: generally friendly gentlemen who i sometimes chat with
column3: once in a while makes uncomfortable comments... i just tend to ignore them and move on. but i ran into him at the local pool
column4: where he made a comment about me wearing a bikini (umm.. should i wear a snowsuit?!) i felt a bit creeped out. especially when next time i saw him at the gym he remarked that he had last seen me in a bikini and ""liked that better"". i rolled my eyes and told him ""well summer is over""
column5: plugged my earphones back in and continued my workout. he hasn't tried to talk to me again
column6: so i hope he got the message.
